{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:18:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:18:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15671"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15671"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.62,0.19,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71099"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15671"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7021"},{"type":"tags","id":"7049"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20160"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71099"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe uterus requires specific ligamentous support to maintain its position while allowing for normal physiological movement during pregnancy and childbirth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes the ligamentous support of the uterus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The fundus moves freely while the cervix remains fixed","The broad ligament provides the primary support of the uterus","The round ligaments prevent uterine prolapse","The pubocervical ligament is identical to the cardinal ligament","The uterosacral ligaments attach to the fundus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efundus of the uterus moves freely\u003C/strong\u003E while the cervix remains relatively fixed, which is essential for accommodating changes during pregnancy. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebroad ligament\u003C/strong\u003E is a double fold of peritoneum that provides passage for vessels and nerves but is not the primary support. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eround ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E help maintain anteversion but do not prevent prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese two ligaments serve different anatomical functions - the \u003Cstrong\u003Epubocervical ligament\u003C/strong\u003E provides support to the front wall of the vagina, while the cardinal ligament (also called the transverse cervical ligament) offers lateral support to the cervix. The \u003Cstrong\u003Euterosacral ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E extend from the posterior aspect of the cervix to attach at the sacrum, not at the fundus, and provide support from behind.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main support of the uterus comes from the cardinal ligaments and uterosacral ligaments attaching at the level of the cervix.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The uterus is anchored primarily at the cervix by cardinal (transverse cervical) and uterosacral ligaments","The fundus of the uterus moves freely while the cervix remains relatively fixed","The pubocervical ligament is distinct from the cardinal ligament and supports the anterior vaginal wall"],"references":["Richards JS, Pangas SA. The ovary: basic biology and clinical implications. J Clin Invest. 2010 Apr;120(4):963-72. doi: 10.1172/JCI41350. Epub 2010 Apr 1. PMID: 20364094; PMCID: PMC2846061","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA","Chaudhry SR, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Uterus Round Ligament. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499970/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15671"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56570"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T23:33:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T23:33:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8362"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71099"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t